            Luxury brands saw a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-08-03-2025-h1-1-mixed-but-improving-q4-2024" target="_blank">mixed but improving Q4 2024</a>, with overall sales rising 2% after a 2% decline in Q3. High-end players like Herm√®s (+18%), Richemont‚Äôs Cartier, and Van Cleef & Arpels (+14%) thrived, while Gucci struggled (-24%). The return of aspirational consumers, driven by strategic pricing and product launches, boosts sales. The US market remains strong, but concerns over inflation and new Trump tariffs are growing.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The ‚Äúgreedflation‚Äù trend of excessive price hikes is waning, though moderate increases persist. Analysts foresee a gradual recovery, with <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://www.thedailyupside.com/industries/consumer/prada-defies-luxurys-slump/" target="_blank">China showing early signs of stabilization</a>. The sector is shifting from extreme caution to cautious optimism, with expectations of modest 5% growth in 2025, below the pre-pandemic 8% CAGR.</p>
