          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Why do so many oil-rich countries fail?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/dutch-disease-global-impact-economy.png" alt="The impact of Dutch disease around the world" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>The impact of Dutch disease around the world.</i></p>
        </mj-text> 
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">All oil-rich countries should thrive, but <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-08-03-2025-f1-14-many-struggle-with-corruption" target="_blank">many struggle with corruption</a>, poor leadership, and overdependence on oil. Without planning for the future, their wealth often leads to failure, not success. Why does this happen?</p>  

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Dutch Disease:</strong> When a country exports too much oil, its currency becomes too strong. This weakens other industries (like farming and manufacturing) because their productsbecome too expensive to sell abroad. The chart above depicts oil revenues as a percentage of GDP.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Too much dependence on oil:</strong> If oil prices drop, the economy crashes because nothing else makes money.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Example:</strong> Iraq has massive oil reserves, but instead of building schools, hospitals, or infrastructure, much of the money is mismanaged. Many Iraqis still struggle with poverty and lack of basic services.
          </p>



          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Wars & conflicts:</strong> Different groups fight over oil money, leading to wars and instability.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Foreign Interference:</strong> Other countries try to control the oil, sometimes causing political problems or conflicts.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Example:</strong> In 1953, the UK and the US helped overthrow Iran‚Äôs government to keep control over its oil. This led to decades of conflict between Iran and Western countries.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
